                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d336">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/12339: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Bulgaria</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Earle</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Sofia</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-06-23T12:00:00+02:00"
                            >June 23, 1941—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received 12:28 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>288. First reaction of Bulgarians to Russo-German war are confusion and shock,
                    mainly on account of distinct division of sympathy <pb facs="0329" n="317"
                        xml:id="pg_317"/> for the two countries. Some Bulgarians recall with
                    apprehension Hitler’s words in <hi rend="italic">Mein Kampf</hi> that Slavs were
                    only good to be slaves while others who hitherto looked upon Hitler’s frequent
                    breach of word with equanimity have been struck pretty hard by Hitler’s complete
                    lack of good faith as exemplified by his latest aggression. Others fear
                    involvement of Bulgaria in war.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Earle</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
